<section id="six-harmonies">
        <h2>The Six Harmonies (<span class="chinese-char">六合</span>)</h2>
        <p>The Six Harmonies represent the six most naturally compatible zodiac pairings. These are animals whose Earthly Branches combine to produce a harmonious elemental transformation:</p>
        <table class="elements-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Pair</th><th>Combined Element</th><th>Relationship Quality</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Rat &amp; Ox</td><td>Earth</td><td>Stability, loyalty, deep mutual support</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Tiger &amp; Pig</td><td>Wood</td><td>Generosity, warmth, shared idealism</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Rabbit &amp; Dog</td><td>Fire</td><td>Devotion, trust, emotional security</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Dragon &amp; Rooster</td><td>Metal</td><td>Ambition, precision, mutual admiration</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Snake &amp; Monkey</td><td>Water</td><td>Intelligence, adaptability, strategic alliance</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Horse &amp; Goat</td><td>Fire</td><td>Creativity, passion, artistic synergy</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section id="three-harmonies">
        <h2>The Three Harmonies (<span class="chinese-char">三合</span>)</h2>
        <p>The Three Harmonies group animals that share an elemental affinity through their position on the zodiac wheel, forming cooperative triads:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Water Triad:</strong> Monkey, Rat, Dragon &mdash; <em>Shēn-Zǐ-Chén</em> (<span class="chinese-char">申子辰</span>)</li>
          <li><strong>Wood Triad:</strong> Tiger, Horse, Dog &mdash; <em>Yín-Wǔ-Xū</em> (<span class="chinese-char">寅午戌</span>)</li>
          <li><strong>Fire Triad:</strong> Snake, Rooster, Ox &mdash; <em>Sì-Yǒu-Chǒu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">巳酉丑</span>)</li>
          <li><strong>Metal Triad:</strong> Pig, Rabbit, Goat &mdash; <em>Hài-Mǎo-Wèi</em> (<span class="chinese-char">亥卯未</span>)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Animals within the same triad share cooperative energy and tend to understand each other's motivations intuitively.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="six-clashes">
        <h2>The Six Clashes (<span class="chinese-char">六衝</span>)</h2>
        <p>The Six Clashes pair animals that sit <em>directly opposite</em> each other on the zodiac wheel. Their energies are fundamentally opposed:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Rat &harr; Horse</strong> &mdash; Water vs Fire; careful planning vs impulsive freedom</li>
          <li><strong>Ox &harr; Goat</strong> &mdash; Earthy pragmatism vs artistic sensitivity</li>
          <li><strong>Tiger &harr; Monkey</strong> &mdash; Bold directness vs clever manoeuvring</li>
          <li><strong>Rabbit &harr; Rooster</strong> &mdash; Diplomatic gentleness vs frank outspokenness</li>
          <li><strong>Dragon &harr; Dog</strong> &mdash; Grandiose ambition vs grounded loyalty</li>
          <li><strong>Snake &harr; Pig</strong> &mdash; Calculated reserve vs open generosity</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Clashing pairs can produce tension, but classical analysis notes that awareness of these dynamics allows individuals to transform conflict into complementary growth. A clash does not doom a relationship &mdash; it signals where conscious effort is needed.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="harms">
        <h2>The Six Harms (<span class="chinese-char">六害</span>)</h2>
        <p>The Six Harms describe pairings where hidden resentments and misunderstandings tend to develop over time:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Rat &amp; Goat</li>
          <li>Ox &amp; Horse</li>
          <li>Tiger &amp; Snake</li>
          <li>Rabbit &amp; Dragon</li>
          <li>Monkey &amp; Pig</li>
          <li>Rooster &amp; Dog</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Harms are subtler than clashes. While clashes are overt conflicts, harms manifest as gradual erosion of trust or unexplained friction that builds over time.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="disclaimer">
        <h2>A Classical Perspective</h2>
        <p>Zodiac compatibility based solely on the birth year is the most <em>general</em> level of analysis. A complete assessment in classical Chinese astrology would examine the full <a href="/bazi/">BaZi chart</a> (all four pillars), the <a href="/wuxing/">five element</a> balance of both individuals, and the interactions between all eight Earthly Branches and Heavenly Stems in their combined charts.</p>
        <p>This tool offers a starting point grounded in classical relationships between the twelve Earthly Branches. For deeper analysis, consult a qualified <a href="/directory/">BaZi practitioner</a>.</p>
      </section>
